comment_text:
I already did the de googlefing rabbit hole. To tell you the truth is not worth it. I really think that the most private solutions require a degree of technical skill sufficiently hard enough to repell almost everyone. I am a real advocate for privacy but not when it comes at the expense of trustworthy convenience. If you are a geek like me go for it but you will end up trying to fix things more times than you will want. 
List of reccomendations for anyone interested:
-You have money? go apple. You dont? go linux (stable versions of reputable distros like ubuntu or mint). For phones pixels are alright and much cheaper, but consider calyx os if you like custom distros because in not that restrictive when it comes to google services.
-DO NOT PUT ALL THE EGGS IN ONE BASKET (decentralize email, password managers, vpns, etc).
-Use encrypted email by default (tuta and proton are the most friendly and accesible)
-If you go cloud for storage, for your important documents use end to end encryption services like protondrive or at least encrypt all your files at icloud (yes there is an option that comes deactivated by default).

It is really complicated to escape from the bubble in we all are in terms of communication and technical solutions. In the part of the world where i live i cannot live without whatsapp for example or even instagram for that sort (i need it to work). The same goes for google workspaces, teams, zoom and other software that most of people use and may or may not be the safest or most private solutions. 
Graphene, hardened linux, NAS backups are cool AF solutions for techies, but you need time and patience. Felix has all the money and time in the world, most of the people watching perhaps not. The best solution is a realistic solution not the best one.

That being said it is really cool that Felix gets into the mind of their viewers to make them see why privacy is important, although i disagree with the degree of depth shown to follow.

Biggest thing keeping me from Graphene OS (or other alternatives)... Google Pay (NFC Payments / Contactless Payments / Tap-to-Pay) through phone. I feel much more secure on having payment method available that way. I rather have my phone, and then physical back-up of some cards, then just my physical and have to pay for my Revolut and/or Wise debit cards. (I don't really care about privacy, but it is off-putting to some degree and alternatives are really damn good)
I'm genuinely super scared of going someplace, and then not having money to pay. One reason why I ALWAYS ask "do you have tap-to-pay" (with gesture of using my phone to pay) before ordering anything. Especially abroad as would be worst to have police involved.

I was using EndeavourOS (arch-based) on computer for very long time, then switched back to a very privacy centered alteration of windows 10, and now on Linux Mint recently. Was thinking of EOS mobile but GOS would make more sense, I'll continue to consider but NFC payments is too huge (my banks don't offer through their apps)

Hello, I was on the same journey few years ago and I appreciate what you do :). I wanted to share some nitpicks. I also use Firefox as my main browser but the Firefox was getting significant amount of money for setting Google as default browser - it doesn't necessarily diminishes it as a browser but it's worth knowing if you want to de-googlify.

If it goes for GrapheneOS and turning off apps when you're done with it - I'm not sure what is the goal here. To save memory, save energy or maybe avoid getting notifications from apps you don't use? All I know is that Android(and I believe iOS) keep apps in memory after you stop using it to make it faster and more seamless to switch back into this app. So the idea here is "RAM not used is RAM wasted". They do some interesting things to manage memory, e.g: compress the RAM memory of the app if wasn't used for some specified time. You can kind of observe this when you switch back to the app in "recent apps" menu - some of them come back quickly because they're still in memory and some of them take time to restore its state to RAM. To sum up it's worth considering if it's what you want. I highly recommend "Does Android use more memory than iOS? ‚Äì Gary explains" by Android Authority that dives deeper into this mechanism.

And last and the least in this case - CPU architecture x86_64 is usually referred to as x86(it's not necessarily correct but everyone knows they refer to x86_64 since most of the mainstream CPUs use 64-bit architecture) or simply x86-64 there is no "by" in the name but that's about it. comment_text:
While I agree 100% with the theme of this video, as an IT worker and someone who does a lot of self-hosting myself, I disagree with a lot of how easy and accessible these different solutions are presented.
As for storage / docs / nextcloud / self-hosting in general:
* You need to manage your own security and keep everything up to date, including both the thing you're hosting it on itself AND the open source software youre using to hosst it
* You also need to be thoughtful about the storage device you're using. What happens if it dies? You're going to need to back it up, which means you essentially need 2 servers and double the amount of storage you are actually storing.
* If something in your workflow suddenly stops working, you're the one whos going to take care of it. If you're having a busy week and/or low energy, 
As for AI:
* The model that you're running locally vs the one openai/google/etc is running and the model you're realistically able to run definetly not the same thing. Depending on your usecase, it can suffice but for realistic purposes its probably not a viable alternative
Note taking:
* Remember Joplin notes aren't backed up by default if you're self hosting it.
Password Manager:
* If you need your password locally, but your vault is internet-based, it means you cant figure out your password without internet. It also means if you need to login to a service on someone else's pc/phone, you will either need to type in an extremely long complex password by hand or install your password manager and login on their device.
Search Engine:
* A lot of search engines also work by paying either google and/or bing for search results. Though it still probably tracks you less :)
== Final Prose ==
We need to work for better privacy, and being aware of how much data is collected about you, and privacy focused alternatives are a good start. Surveillance captalism is a curse in itself. But if you don't have the extra time, energy and money needed to get started and maintain your own setup, I really recommend starting in the slow and easy, and maybe just experimenting with other services a bit first before you throw yourself in the deep end.
Thanks for the video!

I hate working on my hardware. I don't mind putting GPU's in (just got a 4070 last year **flex**) and an 8-core Ryzen 7 CPU. the CPU install freaked me out because I had to flash an Asus mobo from 2013 with a 2021 BIOS update. for anyone unfamiliar, flashing a motherboard can literally brick your machine if something goes wrong during the update process. you can't even access your hard drive when you update system BIOS, hence why it is called "flashing"; you have to download the BIOS update, put it on a flash drive, restart the PC and hold "Del" until your motherboard settings open, find the file on the flash, and update. if you're a PC gamer without a whole lot of money to pay someone else to do the work for you, you've probably experienced this situation. stressful! but...when you install a new CPU and start the computer up and everything posts properly, you feel like a total (nerdy) badass. this was fun to watch Felix! so happy for you and your family! ‚ù§

comment_text: The Ad money is about to end for YouTube and TicToc and all this will dry up by 2030. Ads just ARE NOT selling the products advertised. Once this income dies up, a whole lot of people will be hit hard.

I think the trajectory of YouTube as a platform is crazy to have experienced. Like, doing YouTube as a hobby today is way different than it was back in the early 2010s. Nowadays, it just doesn't garner viewership or sub count like it used to 'cause we're so stuck in the "doing the craziest thing" to go viral. A lot of the older youtubers, or rather the ones from the start, did this as a hobby. Didn't have income in mind. Now that YouTube has been basically taken over by who can make the most income the fastest, a lot of the spark that made YouTube so interesting before is gone. If you don't push and push and push content, the viewership doesn't retain, and then you're stuck with having to grind out every day like Pewds or Jack used to do in order to be successful. That then just brings on burn out. People are always like "youtube isn't like what it used to be" and they're right, because YouTube isn't a place for hobbies anymore, it's just become another cesspool of consumerism. Nothing feels genuine anymore because people use this as a job and not a hobby, because treating YouTube as a hobby doesn't generate income. It's why so many other youtubers feel like sellouts, because if they didn't they wouldn't make money.

comment_text:
I love Pewdiepie.

I love Felix.

I love Gamers.

Pewdiepie is part of the fabric of the history of the internet, he is part of what makes us who we are.

When Pewdiepie last updated us and it seemed like he was leaving Youtube, I honestly believed it.

I thought, how amazing is it that one of the best of us, one of the best human beings, gets to be happy being where he wants to be, gets to be happy where he wants to live, gets to be happy with the family he always wanted.

But then, he's back? And at first, I was really happy for him to be back, but now the more I think about it, the more I ask myself. Does Felix want to be back? To be a bro? Or is he struggling to find the balance between his bros and his family? Is he feeling anxiety from this overall feeling that the world is getting worse?

Why does it seem like just when we as an online community, found a way to make money, to achieve our dreams through what we wanted to do, to allow us to live the happy lives we wanted, the advertisers started clawing back money from everyone?

And each economic downturn, it seems like the advertisers push the influencers just a little bit more, and make them make just a little bit less money, while slowly replacing online communities with bots that can dictate the direction of the flow of views/clicks. It's the mfing Algorithm bros. 

We've been talking about it for years.

If you are interested in what I am saying, I put my feelings, my thoughts, my absolute craziness on the superstonks subreddit. Read what I wrote.

I love all of you bros, I love you Felix, I hope we all take care of each other as we head into dark times.

comment_text:
That was one part of art class in school that I hated, they made me draw the shapes first when I could already draw the end result. It used to drive me crazy! It's like being able to calculate geometry, but then being forced to sit through being taught shapes again. 

I will say this, if you get to colour (mostly painting this applies to), you don't have to memorize the colour wheel, but you DO NEED TO LEARN HOW TO REFERENCE AND UNDERSTAND THE COLOUR WHEEL when mixing paint. You can get from any colour to the colour you're wanting if you learn how to use the colourwheel. I used to roll my eyes at the art teacher prattling on about 'complementary colours', but she never taught us how to mix paint to get the colour we needed, using the colour wheel. There were never any demonstrations on turning any colour you have into the colour you needed. (Seems like magic but it's not! It is possible! The huge glob of paint you mixed the wrong colour won't go to waste if you learn the ancient art of colour theory! It will save you money too!) 

I had to watch a very long and boring youtube tutorial to learn colour mixing, but it gave me an astronomical head start in painting - especially jumping into skin tones , there are colours you wouldn't think of to add there but there are so many reds, blues, and yellows in skintones that it's insane - if you don't mix them in, everything just looks wrong. 

So keep at it, study the masters, and fine a good tutorial to learn from! 
Side note: For drawing people, even if it's anime or manga, study anatomy - you don't have to take a class, just run around in your day to day life and study people that you see - someone's sitting in a chair? Mentally map out their skeletal structure, or lines.

comment_text: I'm not sure why the father wasn't with the mother throughout labour, some kind of restriction? I assume the mother went into hospital to be induced, because there is no way to predict when a baby will be born. There may have been a medical reason for the induction, but there wasn't any mention of this. Labour is actually started by the baby, once their lungs have matured a protein is released into the mother's bloodstream starting labour contractions. If labour is forced to happen using induction methods and the baby and mother's body is not ready, this can result in a 'long labour' and increase the need for medical intervention, sometimes ending in a c-section, that wouldn't have been needed if birth wasn't medically managed. It's sad to see that the baby was instantly wrapped in fabric, rather than having immediate skin-to-skin with the mother, which regulates their breathing and temperature naturally. There are a lot of risks for the mother and baby with a c-section birth, it's not a simple or easy 'fix'. A shame for the father to not remain with the baby also after birth, it's a huge experience for the entire family.
